I met with the HOD of the school, Miss Galerma Lillah. Unfortunately, by the time I arrived the school had already closed, and both the EAs and the principal had left. The HOD requested that I return on Monday.  During our discussion, she showed me the timetable she had prepared for the EAs, which already includes the Zazi iZandi program.
The EAs is currently in a class of an absent educator(3 weeks leave). She wanted to be reminded on how to do sessions.

I had a meeting with the principal and the EAs. During the visit, I verified the EAs’ groupings and confirmed that the learners are grouped correctly. I also checked the EA guides to ensure that their groups and assessment results were transferred accurately, which they successfully completed.  The principal developed a schedule for the EAs to implement the program during the last hour of the school day. The meeting was very fruitful, and all parties are aligned. Sessions are scheduled to begin tomorrow.

I met Principal and share with him that Fumisukoma EAs are no longer doing sessions, because the EA from Grade R reported to me that she doesn't have time to do sessions. Morning hours the teacher do her lessons and after break it's graduation practice which Principal wasn't aware of that. Phumelela Nkonyeni her phone was robbed and Principal was aware of that, she asked to knock off early today so that she can purchase a new device
The teacher said she have a lot of work and she needs assistance from EA most of the time, she give EA a chance when they have to.

Upon arriving at Uitenhage Primary School, we observed that the school was very busy. The principal and the HOD were not on-site, as they were conducting interviews elsewhere.  We met with the EAs, who explained that they were unable to conduct sessions yesterday and today because they had been placed in classrooms to assist with class management. The school is currently running assessments throughout the week, which has further affected the scheduling of sessions.  In addition, the school is preparing for a sporting event taking place on Thursday, which has also required additional support from the EAs. As a result, the EAs are primarily assisting in classrooms and with preparations, which has limited the opportunity to conduct regular sessions during this period.

We arrived at Little Flower Primary School, where I introduced Zanele to the two EAs trained at the school. We then held a meeting with the principal and the EAs.  During the meeting, the EAs raised concerns about struggling to find time to implement the program. They explained that their responsibilities in managing classes, supporting ongoing assessments, and preparing for the upcoming Grade R graduation have limited their availability for sessions.  The principal committed to engaging with the teachers to create more space for the program. The EAs also agreed to improve communication by updating the group and notifying us in advance if they are unable to conduct sessions on a given day.

We arrived at Sikhothina Primary School and met with Abongile, the EA responsible for implementing the program. She explained that she recently lost her phone, which is why she had been unreachable by phone and unable to respond in the WhatsApp group.  I introduced Zanele as her new mentor. Abongile confirmed that she will notify us once she has a replacement phone. At present, she is unable to conduct the program as the sessions require access to Teampact via a phone.

column35: When I arrived in her class, I noticed that she was left with a group of learners to facilitate exams because the class teacher was on leave. One observation I made is that Anelisa was not shading on her LKPT and instead was randomly selecting letters to introduce to the learners. I advised her to shade the letters as this helps track which ones have already been introduced.  At the start of her session, the learners were unsettled. She had called them together but only began preparing her materials after doing so, which led to the learners becoming distracted and playing among themselves. Despite this, she managed to regain their attention and begin the session.  Although her session was not perfect, she reviewed and introduced letters that had been taught previously. She then engaged the learners through letter-writing activities, a search-and-find task, and a board game, which helped make the session interactive and enjoyable. She codes her session correct by asking each child to sound out all the letter sound she did.
